Small habits. Massive impact. These everyday Java mistakes cost you readability, performance, and bugs you’ll spend hours tracking down.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

After years of reading, writing, and reviewing Java code, one thing stands out clearly:
🍼 Junior Developers focus on making the code work. Variables go wherever they fit. Loops are written familiarly. Double gets used for money. Boxed types appear everywhere.
🦾 Senior Developers focus on making the code right. They apply small, deliberate habits that prevent bugs, improve readability, and avoid hidden performance traps — before the problems even appear.
None of the patterns below is complicated. But most junior developers have never been explicitly taught them. Let’s fix that.
1️⃣ Minimize the Scope of Local Variables
🍼 Junior Style — Declare everything at the top
public void processOrder(Long orderId) {
Order order;
double total;
String status;
List<Item> items; order = orderRepository.findById(orderId).orElseThrow();
items = order.getItems();
total = calculateTotal(items);
status = total > 500 ? "PRIORITY" : "STANDARD"…
